Naive forecasting

  • The \(R\) number represents the exponential

  • Mathematically correct but does not account for external factors

    • natural immunity
    • re-infection
    • population density

  • \(R\) number alone is called a naive forecasting.

Logarithms are the inverse of exponentials

  • We have \(3^4 = 81\)

    (in words, 3 raised to the power of 4 equals 81)

  • and \(\log_3(81) = 4\)

    (in words, log base 3 of 81 equals 4)

Logarithms are the inverse of exponentials

  • To compute the \(\log_b\) of a number \(N\),

    • we write \(\log_b(N) = x\),

    • equivalent to \(b^x = N\),

    • we find the power \(x\) the base \(b\) is raised to in order to produce \(N\).

  • \(\log_3(81) = 4\) because

  • \(3 \cdot 3 \cdot 3 \cdot 3 = 3^4 = 81\)

The Richter Scale

  • Severity of earthquakes are measured by the height (amplitude) of waves recorded by a seismograph.

  • Richter scale is logarithmic

    \(\log_10(A)\)

  • The next number on the Richter scale represents a magnitude 10 times greater than that of the previous.

  • Logs are useful for compressing scales on graphs

Trash Can Man and the oil tanker

  • An explosion pushes matter (typically gas) out of the way.

  • Shockwaves (loosely speaking) follow the inverse square law:

    \(\text{intensity} = \dfrac{1}{\text{distance}^2}\),

  • and the first law of thermodynamics

    \(\text{Output energy} = \text{input energy} - \text{Work done}\).

  • The shockwave can be followed by heat and negative pressure waves

Big O Notation

Using maths to analyse the efficiency of your code.

Ordnung Notation

  • Expresses time / resources needed to perform a computation

  • We can analyse a task based on the “size” of its input

  • Allows us to compare different methods for completing the same task

  • We represent the size of the input as \(n\), then

  • we write \(\mathcal{O} ( \text{expression in terms of }n )\)

  • what do we mean by size
  • eventually the task becomes intractable

Sorting

  • Given a list of numbers \((a_1,\ldots,a_n)\)

  • Check each pair of adjacent numbers \(a_i,a_{i+1}\)

  • If \(a_i > a_{i+1}\) then swap

  • For example

    • (4 3 2 1)
    • (3 4 2 1)
    • (3 2 4 1)
    • `(3 2 1 4)

  • Repeat until list is sorted.

  • How many comparisons are needed to sort a list of length 4?

Bubble sort

Complexity of \(\mathcal{O}(n^2)\)

See [https://www.sortvisualizer.com/bubblesort/]

Quicksort

  • Splits list in two (usually equal size)
  • Numbers compared against pivot element separating the 2 sublists.
  • Numbers are placed either below or above the pivot.
  • Process is repeated with smaller and smaller sublists (divide an conquer)

Quicksort

Complexity \(\mathcal{O} (n \log n)\)

See [https://www.sortvisualizer.com/]

  • one can “easily” prove that bubble sort always has complexity O(n^2)
  • one can also prove that quicksort has complexity n log n, but they woud need a trick called the Master Theorem

Best and worst sort

Hold up!

  • What do I mean by “best”?

  • Usually: fewest computations

    (minimise the number of comparisons)

  • Sometimes: consumes least amount of memory

  • Occasionally: something else

Best and worst sort

  • Is quicksort always the quickest?

    • If a bad pivot is chosen…
    • quicksort has complexity $(n^2)

  • Mergesort always has complexity \(\mathcal{O}(n \log n)\)

    (see [https://www.sortvisualizer.com/mergesort/])

  • It can be proved that the lower bound on sorting is \(\mathcal{O}(n \log n)\)
